  <h1>Frequently Asked Questions</h1>
  <p class="byline">Reviewed by Ellis Pemberton, Editor-in-Chief. Last updated May 2026.</p>

  <h2>Who has standing to file a wrongful death claim?</h2>
  <p>It depends on the state. Most states give standing to the decedent's "personal representative" (executor or administrator of the estate), who brings the claim on behalf of the statutory beneficiaries. The statutory beneficiaries are typically the surviving spouse, children, and in some states parents or other dependents. A few states permit direct filing by certain survivors without going through the personal representative. See our <a href="/guides/who-can-file-a-wrongful-death-claim">state-by-state guide</a>.</p>

  <h2>How long do I have to file?</h2>
  <p>Statutes of limitations are tighter than for ordinary personal injury. Most states give 2 years from the date of death. Some states give 1 year (Kentucky, Louisiana, Tennessee). A handful give 3 years. Specific case types &mdash; medical malpractice deaths, government defendants &mdash; can have separate shorter periods. Missing the deadline ends the case. See our <a href="/guides/wrongful-death-statute-of-limitations">statute of limitations guide</a> for the state-by-state breakdown.</p>

  <h2>What damages can be recovered?</h2>
  <p>Categories that are typically recoverable include: pre-death medical expenses; pre-death pain and suffering (in states allowing it); funeral and burial costs; lost earnings over the decedent's expected work life; lost benefits; lost household services; loss of consortium (for surviving spouse); loss of parental companionship and guidance (for surviving children); mental anguish of survivors (in states that recognize it as separate); and punitive damages where the conduct was reckless or intentional. Specific allowances vary by state &mdash; some allow them all; some limit non-economic damages; medical malpractice cases may face statutory caps.</p>

  <h2>Are wrongful death settlements taxable?</h2>
  <p>Federal income tax treatment of wrongful death recoveries generally follows the rule for personal injury awards. Damages received "on account of personal physical injuries or physical sickness" are excluded from gross income under 26 U.S.C. &sect; 104(a)(2). This typically covers the lost-earnings, medical, pain-and-suffering, and non-economic components of a wrongful death recovery. Punitive damages, however, are taxable. Interest on a judgment or settlement is taxable. State tax treatment generally follows federal but should be confirmed for the relevant state. An attorney or CPA should review the allocation of any settlement before it's finalized to optimize tax treatment.</p>

  <h2>Is the survival action the same as the wrongful death claim?</h2>
  <p>Not quite. A "survival action" is the decedent's own personal-injury claim that survives their death and is brought by the estate. It covers what the decedent could have recovered had they lived &mdash; pre-death medical bills, pre-death pain and suffering, lost wages between injury and death. A "wrongful death claim" is a separate claim belonging to the survivors for their own loss &mdash; loss of consortium, loss of companionship, loss of financial support. Most cases plead both. Most states allow both; a few combine them or limit one.</p>

  <h2>How is the recovery divided among multiple survivors?</h2>
  <p>State statutes specify the distribution. In most states with surviving spouse and minor children, the spouse receives a share and the children share equally in the remainder. Adult children may or may not share depending on dependency. Parents may inherit if there is no spouse or child. Where multiple potential beneficiaries exist, the court may apportion the recovery based on each beneficiary's individual loss &mdash; a young spouse and minor children might receive more than a long-estranged adult child, for instance.</p>

  <h2>Does it matter whether there was a will?</h2>
  <p>Not directly for the wrongful death claim itself &mdash; the statutory beneficiaries are defined by the state's wrongful death statute, not by the will. But probate administration does proceed in parallel &mdash; the personal representative who brings the claim is typically the same individual administering the estate. If there is no will, the court appoints an administrator. The survival action recovery flows through the estate (and through any creditor claims and probate distribution); the wrongful death recovery goes more directly to the statutory beneficiaries.</p>

  <h2>What if multiple parties are responsible?</h2>
  <p>Joint and several liability rules govern. In states with traditional joint and several, the plaintiff can recover the full judgment from any one defendant who is at fault and that defendant can seek contribution from others. In states with several-only liability, each defendant pays only its proportional share. Comparative fault rules also reduce recovery by any plaintiff fault. See state-specific guidance.</p>

  <h2>What about deaths caused by criminal acts?</h2>
  <p>A wrongful death civil claim can proceed regardless of any criminal prosecution. Civil burden of proof (preponderance) is lower than criminal (beyond reasonable doubt), so a defendant acquitted criminally can still be civilly liable &mdash; the OJ Simpson case is the canonical example. Collection from a criminal defendant may be difficult; insurance may not cover intentional acts. Victim's-compensation funds can supplement recovery in some cases.</p>

  <h2>Does this site provide legal advice?</h2>
  <p>No. We provide general educational content. Case-specific questions require an attorney licensed in your state.</p>
